I remember quite clearly the first website I made. The website was about Antarctica and I was thirteen years old. For some reason, our Math teacher, Madame Krylova decided to take it upon herself to set aside algebra for a few weeks and teach us HTML instead. So we all learnt what `<P>` meant and got to work. At the end of the course, our websites were uploaded to the school server. I remember clearly the feeling when I got home and pulled up the site on our computer. 

I believe in the internet. I think it has the potential to be much more beautiful than it is today, much more human.

<h2>Why does Blot exist?</h2>

<p>
  I like the simplicity and durability of plain text files. For years I’ve used
  text files to store my notes. One day I realized that those text files had
  enough information – in their contents and metadata – to generate a website,
  without interfering with my writing process. So I made Blot.
</p>



<h2>Multiple sites</h2>

<p>
  You can manage multiple sites from the same account. 
</p>



<h2>Language support</h2>
<p>
  Blot is available in English.
</p>

<h2>Is Blot still maintained?</h2>
<p>
  Yes, and <a href="/news">there’s plenty to do</a>.
</p>

<h2>How long has Blot been around?</h2>
<p>
  The first line of code was written in the summer of 2013.
</p>

<h2>How long do you plan to work on Blot?</h2>
<p>For the rest of my life.</p>

